# 3 Carat Pear Shaped Diamond Ring: Prices & Best Picks {{year}}

A 3 carat pear shaped diamond ring at Blue Nile starts at [$45,539 for a natural GIA F-VS1 Ideal stone](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28435605?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and [$5,316 for a lab grown IGI E-VVS1 Ideal stone](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28628628?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — an 88% gap between natural and lab grown at comparable grades. The 3 carat pear shaped diamond ring total ranges from $46,000–$107,000+ for natural with a setting, and $6,000–$14,000 for lab grown with a setting. This guide covers every dimension of the 3ct pear diamond ring: natural GIA pricing, lab grown IGI options, ring settings with prices, the 3.5ct tier, earrings, how the stone looks on hand, and the exact stone-and-setting combinations that produce the best 3ct pear ring at every budget.

The 3 carat pear shaped diamond ring is the entry point to true luxury in the pear diamond category. At approximately 13×8.5mm, a 3ct pear in a solitaire setting covers the full width of most fingers, is unambiguously visible from across the room, and presents an elongated silhouette that no other diamond shape replicates at this size. This is the carat weight where a pear diamond ring stops being a beautiful piece of jewelry and becomes an architectural statement.

## TL;DR: 3 Carat Pear Shaped Diamond Ring — What to Know

- **Natural GIA 3ct pear ring:** Stone [$45,539 F-VS1 GIA 3.13ct](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28435605?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — [$102,925 D-IF GIA 3.09ct](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29015701?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + setting. Ring total $46,000–$107,000+.
- **Lab grown 3ct pear ring:** Stone [$5,316 E-VVS1 IGI](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28628628?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) or [$6,159 D-VVS1 IGI](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27521592?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + solitaire setting. Total ring $6,000–$7,000.
- **Natural vs lab savings at 3ct:** $45,539 natural vs $5,316 lab at comparable grades — **88% savings** — an absolute dollar difference of $40,223 on the stone alone.
- **3.5ct tier:** Natural GIA 3.5ct pear runs ~$70,000–$120,000 for the stone. Lab grown 3.5ct pear runs ~$7,000–$12,000 for the stone.
- **3ct pear on hand:** At 13×8.5mm, a 3ct pear is visible from 10+ feet, covers the knuckle-to-joint span on most fingers, and generates a visible reaction. It reads as "statement jewelry" in every context.
- **Contrarian Truth:** The [$65,090 GIA D-VS1 natural at 3ct](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/24511778?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) costs $19,551 MORE than the [$45,539 F-VS1](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28435605?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for two color grades and zero clarity difference visible to the naked eye. The F-VS1 is the smarter natural 3ct buy.
- **Priority:** → The [IGI D-VVS1 Ideal lab grown 3ct pear at $6,159](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27521592?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + solitaire setting at ~$600 = ring total ~$6,759. Natural buyers: the [$45,539 F-VS1](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28435605?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the correct entry — the only sub-$50K natural GIA 3ct+ pear at Blue Nile. See The Scarcity Multiplier chart below.

## 3 Carat Pear Shaped Diamond Price: Natural GIA

Natural GIA-certified 3ct pear diamonds are among the rarest stones in Blue Nile's entire inventory. At the 1ct tier, Blue Nile carries 30+ natural GIA pear options; at 2ct, inventory narrows to a handful; at 3ct, Blue Nile typically carries three to five natural GIA Ideal-cut pear diamonds total. This is not a temporary inventory gap — it reflects the geological reality that large, clean, well-cut pear diamonds require specific rough crystal formations that become exponentially rarer at 3ct+.

