## 3.5 Carat Pear Diamond Ring

The 3.5 carat pear diamond ring is rare even by the elevated scarcity standards of 3ct. At approximately 14×9mm, a 3.5ct pear is a genuinely extraordinary piece — worn almost exclusively as an heirloom, fashion statement, or investment piece at the natural price tier.

**3.5ct natural pear diamond ring price:**
Natural GIA 3.5ct pear diamonds at Blue Nile appear intermittently — single-digit inventory at any time. When available, D–G color VS1–VVS2 natural GIA 3.5ct pears typically run $70,000–$150,000 for the stone; per-carat pricing typically runs $20,000–$43,000/ct as The Scarcity Multiplier continues its exponential curve above 3ct. Total ring for a natural 3.5ct pear runs $72,000–$155,000+.

**3.5ct lab grown pear diamond ring price:**
Lab grown 3.5ct IGI Ideal pear diamonds at Blue Nile typically run $7,000–$12,000 for the stone — roughly 20–40% above the 3ct lab entry. With a solitaire setting at $600–$1,200, the complete 3.5ct lab grown pear ring total is approximately $7,600–$13,200. For current 3.5ct lab pear availability, see Blue Nile's [lab pear search](https://www.bluenile.com/diamonds/pear-shaped?lab=true&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) filtered to 3.40–3.60ct.

**3ct vs 3.5ct: which to choose:**

| | 3ct Pear Ring | 3.5ct Pear Ring |
|---|---|---|
| Approx. dimensions | 13×8.5mm | 14×9mm |
| Natural GIA stone | $45,539–$102,925 | ~$70,000–$150,000 |
| Lab IGI stone | $5,316–$9,636 | ~$7,000–$12,000 |
| Natural ring total | $46,000–$107,000 | ~$72,000–$155,000 |
| Lab ring total | ~$6,000–$10,900 | ~$7,600–$13,200 |

For natural buyers, the 3ct to 3.5ct jump costs $25,000–$50,000+ extra for approximately 1mm more length. For lab grown buyers, the increment is roughly $1,700–$2,500 for a meaningfully larger stone. At the lab price differential, the 3.5ct upgrade is worth serious evaluation.

## 3 Carat Pear Shaped Diamond Ring on Hand

The 3ct pear shaped diamond ring on hand is one of the most distinctive visual experiences in the diamond jewelry category. At 13×8.5mm, the stone does not just sit on the finger — it occupies it. The elongated silhouette runs parallel to the finger's length, creating a finger-lengthening illusion that makes even wide fingers appear elongated and elegant.

**Visual impact by finger size:**
On slender fingers (size 4–5.5), a 3ct pear ring at 13mm length covers the full knuckle-to-joint span and appears dramatic — the stone-to-finger proportion is bold. On average fingers (size 6–7), the 3ct pear fills the visual center of the hand naturally. On wider fingers (size 7.5+), the 3ct pear's 8.5mm width provides appropriate proportion — the stone is neither lost nor overwhelming.

**Tip orientation:** A 3ct pear ring is almost always worn tip-up (point toward the fingertip) in the classic teardrop orientation. The tip-toward-wrist orientation is occasionally used for east-west 3ct pear settings but is visually unconventional. The standard tip-up orientation at 3ct maximizes the elongating visual effect.

**Movement sparkle at 3ct:** The 3ct pear's larger facet pattern produces more dramatic fire and scintillation movement than smaller pear stones. Under natural light, the stone's brilliance return creates vivid rainbow flashes across its 13mm length. Under artificial light (restaurant settings, event lighting), the 3ct pear produces a continuous sparkle pattern that draws attention at distance. This is the visual argument for the 3ct pear over other shapes at the same carat weight.

For the complete finger-coverage guide, L/W ratio by hand size, and every pear shape's on-hand visual framework, see the [Pear Diamond Size Chart](/pear-diamond-size-chart).

## Color Grade for a 3 Carat Pear Diamond Ring

Color at 3ct is the most important quality variable after cut. The 3ct pear's 13mm length amplifies color concentration at the tip more severely than at 1ct or 2ct — a grade that looks warm-neutral at 2ct can show visible yellowish warmth at the pear tip at 3ct in a white gold setting.

**D–F color (colorless) — recommended for 3ct pear in white metal:**
D, E, and F are the correct color grades for a 3ct pear diamond ring in white gold or platinum — D is the only true colorless, E provides equivalent visual performance to D in nearly all settings. F is the practical floor for a 3ct white metal setting: at 3ct, F color may show detectable warmth at the pear tip under direct LED lighting that a trained eye would notice.

The [F-VS1 natural 3ct at $45,539](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28435605?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is F color — correct for a white gold solitaire, borderline for platinum where the cool metal amplifies any residual warmth.

**G color at 3ct — approach carefully:**
G near-colorless at 3ct pear is acceptable in a yellow gold setting. In white gold or platinum, G at 3ct shows measurable warmth at the pear tip that is visible to an untrained eye under standard lighting. The [G-VS1 natural 3ct at $67,255](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29162003?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is not recommended for white metal at this size — buyers evaluating this stone should request images in the intended setting.

**Yellow or rose gold settings — G through I acceptable:**
In yellow or rose gold, the warm metal fully neutralizes G, H, or I color warmth at 3ct. A G-VS1 natural 3ct pear in a yellow gold solitaire reads as near-colorless. The [G-VS1 at $67,255](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29162003?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is a valid choice for yellow gold — a 3ct natural pear with G color, VS1 clarity, Ideal cut, and GIA certification.

**Lab grown 3ct pear color:** All available lab grown 3ct pear options at D-VVS1 and E-VVS1 are high color grades — D or E. There is no reason to accept lower color in lab grown when D and E are the default pricing tier.

## What to Check Before Buying a 3ct Pear Shaped Diamond

At $5,316–$102,925 for the stone alone, the pre-purchase checklist for a 3ct pear diamond is not optional. A single proportions defect on a stone in this price range costs $40,000–$100,000 to resolve.

**Certificate:** GIA or IGI only. Verify the report number at gia.edu or igiworldwide.com. At 3ct, an uncertified stone is not a savings opportunity — it is an unquantifiable risk on a six-figure stone position.

**L/W ratio:** Target 1.55–1.65 for a solitaire ring. At 3ct, this produces a 13mm-long stone — the optimal elongated silhouette. Above 1.70, the stone appears narrow and blade-like at this size. Below 1.45, the 3ct pear begins to approximate a round visually and loses its primary shape advantage.

**Depth %:** Target 58–62%. A 3ct pear at 65%+ depth hides significant mass below the girdle — you are paying 3ct prices for a stone that presents face-up like a 2.5ct. Reject any 3ct pear with depth above 63%.

**Bow-tie check — mandatory at 3ct:** Watch the 360° video on every 3ct pear before purchase. At 3ct, the bow-tie shadow is at its maximum potential. The larger facet pattern amplifies the contrast between the bow-tie shadow and the surrounding brilliance — a minor bow-tie at 1ct becomes a visible defect at 3ct. A light, narrow bow-tie is acceptable; a dark band across the center is not — only the video reveals which category each stone falls into.

**Symmetry:** GIA Excellent only at 3ct. At 13mm, any asymmetry in the shoulder arcs, tip position, or belly width is visible to the naked eye without a loupe. A pear with Excellent cut but mismatched shoulders at 3ct still looks off — review all symmetry parameters on the certificate and in the video. See the complete cut framework in the [Pear Diamond Ideal Proportions Guide](/pear-diamond-ideal-proportions).

**Fluorescence:** For D–F natural 3ct pear diamonds, strong fluorescence is a risk factor at this size — at 3ct, fluorescence haze under UV-heavy light is more visible across a larger facet surface. Faint or None fluorescence is the safe choice.

## 3 Carat Pear Shaped Diamond Earrings

A 3 carat pear shaped diamond earrings query typically refers to a pair of pear drop earrings totaling 3 carats — either 1.5ct per ear (3CTW) or 3ct per ear (6CTW, extremely rare). The practical interpretation for most buyers is 3CTW: two matched pear diamonds at approximately 1.5ct each.

**3CTW lab grown pear drop earrings:**
Two matched 1.5ct lab grown pear diamonds at approximately 0.75ct each provide a smaller 3CTW alternative; at exactly 1.5ct per ear, full 3CTW lab pear earrings require two stones from the lab 1.5ct pear inventory at Blue Nile. Pricing for two matched 1.5ct IGI D-VVS1 lab pear stones: approximately $1,200–$2,000 per stone = $2,400–$4,000 for the pair. Add pear drop earring settings in 14K white gold ($400–$900 per pair) for a total 3CTW lab pear earring cost of approximately $2,800–$4,900.

**3CTW natural pear drop earrings:**
Two matched 1.5ct natural GIA pear diamonds at comparable grades (E–G, VS1–VS2) run approximately $5,000–$9,000 per stone at Blue Nile — $10,000–$18,000 for the pair of loose stones. Add earring settings for a total of $10,400–$18,900 for 3CTW natural pear drop earrings. For all pear earring CTW configurations, settings, and pricing, see the [Pear Shaped Diamond Earrings Guide](/pear-shaped-diamond-earrings).

